ing of animal studies in and beyond the academy have given rise to questions about the nature of humanity. Using sources from the life sciences, literature, visual art, poetry, philosophy, and photography, this collection interrogates not animal or machine emotions per se, but rather uses animals and machines as lenses through which to investigate human emotions and the affective entanglements between humans and non-humans. The COVID-19 pandemic made us more keenly aware of the importance of both animals and new technologies in our daily lives, and this volume ultimately sheds light on the centrality of non-humans in the human emotional world and the possibilities that relationships with non-humans offer for enriching that world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAnimals in literature. 0aAnimals in mass media. 0aComputers in literature. 0aGerman literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aTechnology in popular culture. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aHistory of emotions.  aemotions and non-humans.  aliterary and cultural animal studies.  arobots in fiction.1 aHillard, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeonard, Sarah L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartz, Brett, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeirosu, Madalina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyertholen, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMueller-Greene, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoley, Jared, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQuinn, Erika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQuinn, Erika, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt